# {{senseid|en|inserted between}} {{lb|en|linguistic morphology}} An [[empty morph]] (meaningless morph) inserted between two [[morphemes]] in the process of word formation, such as English {{m|en|-o-}}, {{m|en|-i-}}.
#* '''2004''', Francis Katamba, ''Morphology: Critical Concepts in Linguistics''[https://books.google.com/books?id=QBsKpjIh3J8C&pg=PA187&dq=%22interfix%22], {{ISBN|0415270790}}, page 187:
#*: An empty morph is an '''interfix''' if it fulfills all of the following three conditions (Dressier, 1985f).
# {{lb|en|linguistic morphology}} A [[transfix]].
# {{lb|en|computing|information retrieval|dated}} An [[association link]], a device to group multiple words or concepts.
#* '''1959''', Frank S. Wagner, Jr., ''A Dictionary of Documentation Terms''[http://books.google.com/books?id=MlgZAAAAMAAJ], page 19:
#*: LOCANT, n. A number used in the Dyson cipher system for coding the position of substituents of carbon chain, i.e. an '''interfix'''.

====Usage notes====
* The term is absent from general English dictionaries. Compared to terms ''prefix'', ''suffix'' and ''affix'', ''interfix'' is very rare.<ref>{{R:GNV|prefix,suffix,affix,(interfix*500)}}</ref>

